The paper deals with graph algorithms and their complexity, specifically the problem of computing a Mondshein sequence. This problem involves concepts from graph drawing, graph encoding, and visibility representations, which are typically studied in the computational geometry (cs.CG) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of non-separating ear decomposition, which is a graph-theoretic concept that falls under the sub-categories of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and graph theory (cs.GT). Finally, the paper presents an algorithm that improves the running time of several other graph problems, which suggests that numerical analysis (cs.NA) may also be relevant.
